âœ… QUESTION 1: SET MATRIX ZEROES

ğŸ“Œ Very frequently asked in interviews (Amazon, Microsoft, Google)
ğŸ“Œ Concepts: 2D Array, In-place algorithm, Optimization

ğŸ” Problem Statement

You are given an m x n integer matrix.

ğŸ‘‰ If any element is 0, set its entire row and entire column to 0.

âš ï¸ Important:
You must do this in-place (without using extra space like another matrix).

ğŸ§ª Example

Input:

Matrix:
[
 [1, 1, 1],
 [1, 0, 1],
 [1, 1, 1]
]


Output:

[
 [1, 0, 1],
 [0, 0, 0],
 [1, 0, 1]
]


Explanation:

The element at position (1,1) is 0

So â†’ Row 1 and Column 1 are set to 0

ğŸ§  Optimized Algorithm (Interview-Preferred)
ğŸ’¡ Key Idea:

Use the first row and first column as markers instead of extra space.

ğŸ› ï¸ Steps

1ï¸âƒ£ Check if the first row contains any 0
2ï¸âƒ£ Check if the first column contains any 0
3ï¸âƒ£ Traverse the remaining matrix:

If matrix[i][j] == 0

Mark matrix[i][0] = 0

Mark matrix[0][j] = 0
4ï¸âƒ£ Update matrix using markers
5ï¸âƒ£ Finally update first row & column if needed

â±ï¸ Complexity Analysis
Type	Value
Time	O(m Ã— n)
Space	O(1) (in-place)
ğŸ’» Java Code (Clean & Interview-Ready)
class Solution {
    public void setZeroes(int[][] matrix) {

        int rows = matrix.length;
        int cols = matrix[0].length;

        boolean firstRowZero = false;
        boolean firstColZero = false;

        // Step 1: Check first column
        for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
            if (matrix[i][0] == 0) {
                firstColZero = true;
                break;
            }
        }

        // Step 2: Check first row
        for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
            if (matrix[0][j] == 0) {
                firstRowZero = true;
                break;
            }
        }

        // Step 3: Mark rows & columns
        for (int i = 1; i < rows; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j < cols; j++) {
                if (matrix[i][j] == 0) {
                    matrix[i][0] = 0;
                    matrix[0][j] = 0;
                }
            }
        }

        // Step 4: Update matrix using markers
        for (int i = 1; i < rows; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j < cols; j++) {
                if (matrix[i][0] == 0 || matrix[0][j] == 0) {
                    matrix[i][j] = 0;
                }
            }
        }

        // Step 5: Update first column
        if (firstColZero) {
            for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
                matrix[i][0] = 0;
            }
        }

        // Step 6: Update first row
        if (firstRowZero) {
            for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
                matrix[0][j] = 0;
            }
        }
    }
}

ğŸ§¾ Line-by-Line Explanation (Simple)
boolean firstRowZero = false;
boolean firstColZero = false;


â¡ï¸ To remember if first row or column must be zeroed later.

if (matrix[i][0] == 0)


â¡ï¸ Check if any element in first column is zero.

matrix[i][0] = 0;
matrix[0][j] = 0;


â¡ï¸ Use first row & column as markers.

if (matrix[i][0] == 0 || matrix[0][j] == 0)


â¡ï¸ If row or column is marked â†’ set cell to zero.
